  sequentialGlobal.execute(r);
}
// and await termination.
sequentialGlobal.awaitTermination(timeout, timeUnit);
```
It works this way: the sequential executors, are single thread executors that [guarantee sequential execution of the tasks in the order they are added][1]. And the parallel executor creates a thread for each task.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/Executors.html#newSingleThreadExecutor--

In general:

- To run tasks in parallel just executed the on a `ExecutorService` and a `Executors.newCachedThreadPool()` could be a good default choice. 
- When you want to run asynchronous tasks sequentially in the same thread just use `.thenApply(...)`
- Use `.join()` to stop and wait for a result of the execution
- Use `CompletableFuture.allOf` to have a single `CompletableFuture` of few


In you case it could be something like:

    ExecutorService executor = Executors.newCachedThreadPool()

    Supplier&lt;String&gt; task1 = { &quot;task1&quot; }
    Function&lt;String, String&gt; task2 = { it + &quot; -&gt; task2&quot; }
    Function&lt;String, String&gt; task3 = { it + &quot; -&gt; task3&quot; }
    Supplier&lt;String&gt; task4 = { &quot;task4&quot; }
    
    CompletableFuture&lt;String&gt; task3result = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(task1, executor)
            .thenApply(task2)
            .thenApply(task3)
    
    CompletableFuture&lt;String&gt; task4result  = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(task4, executor)
    
    Function&lt;Void, String&gt; merge123and4 = {
        &quot;[[&quot; + task3result.join() + &quot;] + &quot; + task4result.join() + &quot;]&quot;
    }
