Your actual approach is the way to go.  I would forget about using `StringBuilder` for this.  But here is a related suggestion.
If you want to ensure that existing strings in the array are not already prefixed with an @ sign, then do it as follows using [String.replaceAll](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#replaceAll(java.lang.String,java.lang.String)).  This also enforces word boundaries so if any names are part of an existing word (e.g. `Same vs Sam`) it won&#39;t be changed.
```
String[] names = {&quot;DonaldTrump&quot;, &quot;JoeBiden&quot;};
    
String s = &quot;It seems like DonaldTrump and JoeBiden will both run for president in 2024.&quot;;
```
- `(?&lt;!@)` - Is a negative look-behind assertion which says `@` does not occur before name. 

- `\\b` - enforces word boundaries.  Suggested by [Maarten Bodewes](https://stackoverflow.com/users/589259/maarten-bodewes)
```
for (String name : names) {
        s = s.replaceAll(&quot;\\b(?&lt;!@)&quot;+name+&quot;\\b&quot;, &quot;@&quot;+name);
}
System.out.println(s);

The purpose of the StringBuilder class is to create a mutable sequence of characters, since the String class is immutable.

I don&#39;t think in your case is necessary since you can use something like this:
```

    for( String username: usernames ) {
            s = s.replace(username, &quot;@&quot; + username);

   }
```

But assuming the purpose is to understand how StringBuilder works, here is an updated function that uses the StringBuilder class:

```
        public String highlightUsernames(String tweetText, String[] usernames) {
         // You can create an instance of the StringBuilder class with the tweetText String.
            StringBuilder stringBuilder = new StringBuilder(tweetText);
        
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; usernames.length; i++) {
                
                // Get the index of the user
               int index = stringBuilder.indexOf(usernames[i]);
               
               // And use the insert method of StringBuilder to add the &quot;@&quot; before the username if it&#39;s found
               if (index != -1) {
                    stringBuilder.insert(index, &quot;@&quot;);
                }
            }
            
            // At the end, you can convert the StringBuilder to a String, using its toString method
            return stringBuilder.toString();

```

Using StringBuilder will give a better performance in this case. here&#39;s a simple implementation:

    public String highlightUsernames(String tweetText, String[] usernames) {

        StringBuilder  resultText = new StringBuilder(tweetText) ;

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; usernames.length; i++) {
            var index = 0;
            while (true) {
                index = resultText.indexOf(usernames[i], index);
                if (index == -1)
                    break;
                resultText.insert(index, &quot;@&quot;);
                index +=2;
            }
        }
        return resultText.toString();
    }

Let&#39;s dive deep into this and make something really performant. It uses the smarts of regular expressions to find all names at once, and then inserts the @ symbol if there isn&#39;t one already. It stores the indexes, so that any string copying only has to be performed once (or twice when you call `StringBuilder#toString()` of course).

It also fixes a major issue with your code: that it matches `&quot;JoeBiden&quot;` in `&quot;JoeBidenAgain&quot;` by using *word boundaries*. Actually, a Java/regex &quot;word&quot; character nicely coincides with the rules for Twitter names / handles (probably that&#39;s not coincidental).

```

String[] names = {&quot;DonaldTrump&quot;, &quot;JoeBiden&quot;};

String namesForRegexp = Arrays.stream(names).map(s -&gt; Pattern.quote(s)).collect(Collectors.joining(&quot;|&quot;));
Pattern p = Pattern.compile(&quot;\\b(?&lt;!@)(&quot; + namesForRegexp + &quot;)\\b&quot;);

String s = &quot;It seems like DonaldTrump and JoeBidenAgain will both run for president in 2024.&quot;;

Matcher m = p.matcher(s);
List&lt;Integer&gt; insertionPoints = new LinkedList&lt;&gt;();
while (m.find()) {
	// do our own lookbehind for existing @ sign
	insertionPoints.add(m.start());
}

StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(s.length() + insertionPoints.size());
int offset = 0;
for (int insertionPoint : insertionPoints) {
	sb.append(s.substring(offset, insertionPoint));
	sb.append(&#39;@&#39;);
	offset = insertionPoint;
}
sb.append(s.substring(offset));

System.out.println(sb);
```

This will print out:

``` none
It seems like @DonaldTrump and JoeBidenAgain will both run for president in 2024.
```

Note that `&quot;JoeBidenAgain&quot;` is now not tagged with a `@` sign, that&#39;s probably somebody else after all.

---

**Tweets are deliberately small**, so this kind of unnecessary optimization would not make much sense for an actual tweet; it should be more of an illustration on how to generally optimize such a function.

